<DOC><DOCNO> AP880506-0258 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0106EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-AlleghenyInternational     05-06 0178</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Allegheny International,0185</SECOND><HEAD>Allegheny Creditors Seeking To Halt Proxy Fight</HEAD><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A bankruptcy court judge has scheduled ahearing on a request by Allegheny International Inc.'s unsecuredcreditors to halt a proxy fight being waged by two investment firmsfor control of the company.   Judge Joseph Cosetti set a hearing for next Thursday over thecreditors' request to block the firms, Spear Leeds andamp; Kellogg andBomar Holdings, from trying to gain control of the 13-member boardin a May 20 shareholder vote.   The dissident firms contend Allegheny International's topmanagers are more interested in keeping their jobs than inpreserving shareholders' interests as the company reorganizes underfederal bankruptcy protection from creditors.   The firms are trying gain seven seats on the company's board.   On Thursday, Allegheny International announced it planned tosend letters to shareholders urging them to oppose the dissidentshareholders group. But the company later said it had canceledthose plans.   Allegheny International's prime businesses are the consumerproducts produced by Sunbeam, Oster, Northern Electric,Almet-Lawnlite, Springfield Instrument, Soloray and Hanson Scale.</TEXT></DOC>